Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:40:26.658Z]: now can factors be prime, composite or both?

Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:49:11.359Z]: not quite but you can look up what prime means
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T00:50:49.511Z]: i did
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:51:02.606Z]: ok so what is a prime number?

Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:53:20.967Z]: super!
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:53:49.599Z]: so lets compare numbers 1, 2 , and 4
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:53:59.856Z]: how many factors make up the 1?
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T00:55:24.709Z]: 0
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:56:31.191Z]: well remember what factors are: 2 numbers multiplied to get a product
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T00:56:49.332Z]: 1
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:57:33.972Z]: ok so really 1 has a factor 1  and itself right?
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T00:57:42.333Z]: yes
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:58:14.570Z]: ok so what kind of number is 1
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T00:58:55.733Z]: not a prime numbers
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T00:59:21.095Z]: ok can you explain not?
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T00:59:58.115Z]: i mean it is not a prime number
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:00:31.317Z]: Fantastic thinking! 1 is unique so it is not considered a prime number. what other numbers are prime?

Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:04:30.345Z]: ok so how are you getting these numbers? what is your reasoning?
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T01:06:21.333Z]: because it says 1 is not a prime number
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:06:49.697Z]: ok but we need to know why :)
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:07:25.899Z]: so what are the factors of 2?

Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:09:04.481Z]: 2 x 1 = 2
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:09:11.331Z]: are there any other factors of 2?
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T01:09:25.925Z]: 2
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:09:54.017Z]: ok what other factor goes with 2 ?
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T01:10:14.156Z]: 4
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:11:05.037Z]: so you are saying that there is 4 x ? = 2
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T01:11:26.841Z]: n0
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:11:44.432Z]: ok so the only true factors of 2 are 2x1
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:11:51.994Z]: does that make sense?
Jenelle @ [2018-05-09T01:12:05.549Z]: yes
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:12:21.016Z]: so lets categorize it on the whiteboard
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:12:33.614Z]: what about 3

Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:15:14.989Z]: you can be honest

Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:17:14.296Z]: 8 is the product or the answer to a multiplication problem
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:17:34.012Z]: the 4 and 2 are the factors

Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:22:13.414Z]: ok so because eight has 2 pairs of factors it is COMPOSITE

Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:29:00.946Z]: ok so lets make some observations based on the other equivalent fractions
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:29:16.759Z]: for example
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:29:22.213Z]: Do you see the whiteboard?

Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:30:03.566Z]: how are 3 and 6 similar?
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:30:21.208Z]: you multiply by 2??
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:31:00.187Z]: yes! perfect! so 6 is part of the 3 multiple family
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:31:22.825Z]: yep
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:32:02.078Z]: one observation is that in order to have equivalent fractions, the numerators have to share a common multiple
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:32:06.545Z]: does that make sense?
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:32:38.037Z]: kinda could you explain a little more please
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:32:41.859Z]: sure
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:33:06.004Z]: thank you
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:33:26.579Z]: the green numbers are all multiples
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:33:38.993Z]: do you see that?
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:34:10.876Z]: yes and the red numbers are what you multiplying by right
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:34:45.684Z]: well the red number is the number family
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:35:01.053Z]: it is what you are skip counting by
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:35:07.114Z]: oh
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:35:18.166Z]: 3,6,9,12,
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:35:31.948Z]: then what comes next if we are skip counting by 3?
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:35:55.493Z]: 15,18,21,24,27
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:36:09.202Z]: Fantastic thinking! those multiples could go on and on!
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:36:29.509Z]: now when we compare fractions the numerators have to share a common multiple
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:36:39.546Z]: which we decided was 6
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:37:19.016Z]: would we multiply by 6 then
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:37:22.628Z]: are you with me?
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:37:33.597Z]: yepp
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:37:41.616Z]: well how did you think about multiplying by six?
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:38:55.361Z]: cause  both 3 and 6 have a multiple of 6
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:39:34.007Z]: ok i see! but actually we would find the factor that would could use to relate the two numbers
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:40:02.401Z]: what do u mean by relate
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:40:16.588Z]: what numbers 3 x ? = 6
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:40:24.152Z]: 2
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:40:37.572Z]: super that is called the common factor
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:40:48.723Z]: oh ok.
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:41:13.303Z]: so what we do to the NUMERATOR with the common factor we have to also do to the DENOMINATOR
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:41:52.218Z]: And thats a way we can get equivalent fractions
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:41:53.753Z]: find common factors ?
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:42:10.207Z]: well common multiples
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:42:27.297Z]: then fill in the factors to make the equation true
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:42:49.479Z]: so lets try the bottom one and walk me thru it
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:43:26.538Z]: whats your first thought?
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:44:36.686Z]: i honestly  cant remember much after like 5 minutes thats why i need extra help in math cause i have difficulties understanding it
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:44:49.218Z]: Please give it a try! It is okay to make mistakes.
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:45:19.158Z]: would we multily by 2
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:45:26.749Z]: ***multiply
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:45:59.705Z]: ok so essentially we would just be doubling the fraction right when we multiply by 2 right?
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:46:07.985Z]: we can do that :)
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:46:21.329Z]: yes
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:46:40.283Z]: so we have to do the same to the top
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:46:46.683Z]: 8/12
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:46:52.881Z]: wu/
RILEY @ [2018-05-09T03:46:55.354Z]: is that the answer
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:46:56.758Z]: I think you have it from here! Keep up the awesome work!
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T03:47:01.288Z]: Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!

Daniel @ [2018-05-09T01:54:34.338Z]: The ratio.
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:54:47.065Z]: super! so what is the ratio?
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T01:54:56.210Z]: l=w
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T01:55:11.362Z]: l*w=a
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:55:11.523Z]: Can you say more about how you got that?
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:55:23.680Z]: what does l mean?
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T01:55:38.045Z]: The length times the width equals the area
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:55:55.351Z]: ok thats the area but not the ratio
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:55:59.142Z]: ok Let's take a look at an example together.
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:57:11.045Z]: so lets say the smaller square is 1/2 scale drawing of the orginial and bigger figure
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:57:39.986Z]: that means the smaller square is 1/2 smaller than the bigger one
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:57:56.406Z]: or the bigger square is twice as big as the small one
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:58:01.241Z]: does that make sense?
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T01:58:05.311Z]: Yes
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T01:58:48.367Z]: That means the smaller square is half the size as the bigger
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T01:59:03.196Z]: whih means the smaller square is 2
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:59:03.917Z]: ok so how can we figure out the length of the smaller square! and yes thats right
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:59:07.322Z]: Fantastic thinking!
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T01:59:42.422Z]: how did you get 2 by the way?
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T02:00:49.718Z]: Because 4 divided by 1/2 is 2 because i already knew half of four is two
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T02:01:02.746Z]: nice! so you divided :)
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T02:01:11.679Z]: so what would be the width?
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T02:01:12.513Z]: In my head yes.
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T02:01:33.394Z]: the width would b 3
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T02:01:34.150Z]: the width of the smaller one
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T02:01:50.459Z]: be*
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T02:02:02.470Z]: yes
Daniel @ [2018-05-09T02:02:26.771Z]: Great
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T02:02:38.826Z]: I think you have it from here! Keep up the awesome work!
Ms. Johana  @ [2018-05-09T02:02:41.624Z]: Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!

RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:12:16.059Z]: what is 7 halfs = to
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:12:20.877Z]: what does a denominator *(the bottom of a fraction)* tell us about a whole object?
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:12:54.819Z]: a denominator is the whole
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:13:02.342Z]: Okay, for example, how many equal parts would 3/4 have in 1 whole?
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:13:21.488Z]: 4 fourths
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:13:33.715Z]: i dont know that much
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:13:42.296Z]: Right! :) So for example, if we have 8/4...how many wholes can we make?
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:13:51.019Z]: 2
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:14:01.446Z]: How do you know?
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:14:24.931Z]: because 2 times 4 = 8
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:14:36.729Z]: Okay, look at 9/4... how many wjholes can we make?
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:14:39.038Z]: wholes*
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:14:44.277Z]: 5
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:15:12.997Z]: Not exactly, how many parts make up 1 whole in 9/4?
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:16:25.397Z]: i forgot what it is scence 3rd grade
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:16:45.311Z]: sence
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:16:51.612Z]: Please think about what we just talked about :)
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:18:20.479Z]: 2 and 1/4
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:18:29.400Z]: How do you know? :)
RAWLSTON @ [2018-05-09T21:19:36.487Z]: because if you times 4 and 2 that we talked about and you add 1/4 to the number it will equal 9/4
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:19:54.374Z]: Great! See if you can use what we did to try this on your own. Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!
lesson_name: Writing Fractions as Mixed Numbers and Mixed Numbers as Fractions

Evolet @ [2018-05-08T15:06:49.182Z]: or 8
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-08T15:07:10.423Z]: 8/4... the 4 is how many part make up 1 whole... what does the 8 mean?

Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:01:10.132Z]: I can see the problem, but only the answer you had when you clicked in
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:01:28.926Z]: oh
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:01:51.678Z]: Why do you think the first answers are ones?
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:02:41.548Z]: yes so  the 8 in 18 i in the ones place
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:03:48.755Z]: Right, what if we had 150 ÷ 3... how many groups of 15 can we make?
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:04:23.251Z]: 5
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:04:35.182Z]: Not exactly, try again :)
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:04:59.244Z]: 10
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:05:47.950Z]: Right! :) So if we have groups of 15... how many will go in each of 3 groups?
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:06:26.839Z]: 5
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:06:39.004Z]: or 10
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:06:58.700Z]: Which one?
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:07:07.022Z]: 1
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:07:11.190Z]: 10
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:08:07.872Z]: Do you see that we can can make 3 groups of 50 to get 150?
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:09:32.232Z]: this is hard i give up
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:09:59.650Z]: Don't give up! :)Think of it this way:  How many groups of 10 make up 150?
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:10:38.148Z]: 3
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:10:54.532Z]: Not exactly, if you break 150 into groups of 10, how many can you make?
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:11:37.694Z]: 15
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:11:46.661Z]: Right! :) So if we split the 15 tens into groups of 3, how many tens will be in each group?
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:13:13.182Z]: 5
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:13:31.682Z]: Great! :) So then 150 ÷ 3 is the same as 5 tens or 50. make sense?
Jayla @ [2018-05-09T22:14:31.717Z]: im ok whit it
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:14:43.445Z]: See if you can use what we did to try this on your own. Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!

Maya @ [2018-05-09T22:14:11.395Z]: 3
Maya @ [2018-05-09T22:14:14.759Z]: 3 parts
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:14:32.294Z]: Please think about what we just talked about :)
Maya @ [2018-05-09T22:14:52.894Z]: then 4 equal parts?
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:15:26.196Z]: Right! So then if we have a denominator of 4... what fraction would mean the same as 1/2
Maya @ [2018-05-09T22:16:09.814Z]: 2/4?
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:16:25.509Z]: Right! How do you know?
Maya @ [2018-05-09T22:16:41.727Z]: because you can divide to find them
Maya @ [2018-05-09T22:16:47.791Z]: like reduce them
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:17:17.370Z]: Do you see that 2 is **half** of 4
Maya @ [2018-05-09T22:17:22.475Z]: yes
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:18:20.293Z]: Okay, now think of 2/5... is the more or less than 1/2?
Maya @ [2018-05-09T22:18:46.427Z]: more?
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:19:21.893Z]: If the denominator is 5... what amount is half of 5?
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T22:21:52.856Z]: Are you still there?

transcript:

Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-10T00:55:46.723Z]: What does **math help 2** tell us about our answer when we **divide** the same top number by the same bottom number in a fraction?
ASHER @ [2018-05-10T00:59:25.923Z]: Dividing the numerator and denominator of a fraction by the same number will have an equivalent fraction
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-10T00:59:43.456Z]: For example: 3/3 = ?
ASHER @ [2018-05-10T01:00:09.817Z]: 1 whole.
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-10T01:00:17.189Z]: So then if we have 6/8 ÷ 1, we can say that the value of the fraction does **not** change. Right?
ASHER @ [2018-05-10T01:00:39.603Z]: Yeah.
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-10T01:00:45.627Z]: We can also say that since we know the 2/2 = 1, that 6/8 ÷ 2/2  also does **not** change the value of the fraction. Make sense? :).
ASHER @ [2018-05-10T01:01:02.962Z]: Yes.
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-10T01:01:08.686Z]: See if you can use what we did to try this on your own. Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!

Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:32:17.295Z]: Type
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:32:31.543Z]: How many acres does it say there are in **total**?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:33:01.146Z]: 3
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:33:09.336Z]: How many acres are there in the first 4 lots in total?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:33:35.227Z]: 7/4
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:33:48.058Z]: Not exactly, what math can we use to find out?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:34:03.484Z]: Addition
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:34:06.936Z]: What will we add?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:34:33.055Z]: 3/4+1/4+2/4+3/4
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:34:50.560Z]: Awesome, what does that equal?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:35:26.286Z]: Um...9/4
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:35:50.915Z]: No
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:35:55.883Z]: right! How is that more or less than 2 wholes
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:35:57.580Z]: Oops
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:36:16.455Z]: That is less than one whole
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:36:25.868Z]: More that one whole
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:36:31.942Z]: Sorry
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:36:33.502Z]: Is it more than 2 wholes?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:36:38.653Z]: No
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:36:53.495Z]: what does the 4 in 9/4 tell us?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:37:18.991Z]: Total parts in one whole
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:37:55.850Z]: Yes, so if we have **9**/4... can we make more than 1 whole?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:38:09.090Z]: Yes
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:38:55.687Z]: can we make more than 2 wholes?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:39:11.488Z]: No
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:39:37.965Z]: but we know that the 4 tells us how much makes up 1 whole, right
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:39:45.631Z]: Yes
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:39:58.898Z]: And 4/4 is 1 whole.... what fraction is the same as 2 whoels?
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:40:00.701Z]: wholes*
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:41:18.794Z]: ummmmmmmm...
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:41:46.527Z]: Please give it a try! It is okay to make mistakes.
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:41:50.927Z]: It’s hard
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:42:10.683Z]: I don’t know
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:42:23.941Z]: Do you see that **8**/4 would be the same as 2 wholes?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:42:33.677Z]: No
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:42:41.468Z]: How
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:43:30.955Z]: the 4 tells us how many parts will make up 1 whole. So **4**/4 tells us we have 4 parts out of 4 parts... good so far?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:44:34.912Z]: Oh I get it because 4+4=8 two wholes would be 8/4
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:44:59.820Z]: Right! :)
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:45:05.025Z]: So then is 9/4 more or less than 8/4?
Paige @ [2018-05-09T21:45:33.182Z]: More so it is bigger than two wholes
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:46:12.958Z]: Right! :) So now find out how many acres we still need in lot 5 to get to a total of 3 acres :)
Ms. Meaghan @ [2018-05-09T21:46:16.729Z]: Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!
lesson_name: Adding and Subtracting Fractions with Like Denominators in Real-World Situations

Sara @ [2018-05-08T17:44:05.531Z]: Okay

TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:10:05.355Z]: ready
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:10:21.595Z]: how would you describe a **midpoint** ?
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:10:52.876Z]: i dont know
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:11:00.197Z]: im sorry
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:11:12.588Z]: it's okay, let's check it out together
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:11:17.157Z]: ok
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:11:35.558Z]: My friend lives *halfway* between my house and the school.  I can call her home the **midpoint**, what do you think that means?
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:12:04.050Z]: in the middle
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:12:11.208Z]: that's right, exactly the middle :)
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:13:08.823Z]: If B is our midpoint, where would the end be?
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:14:20.263Z]: would it be on the bottom
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:14:39.137Z]: right, we're going to move the same distance from A to B but in the opposite direction
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:14:58.401Z]: ok
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:15:00.293Z]: What would the new coordinates be for C
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:15:58.900Z]: to the right 2 and then up 1
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:16:26.730Z]: -2-2
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:16:57.916Z]: I like that you kept the x-coordinate the same :)  that's great.  We just want to move one space down on the y though
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:17:37.688Z]: ok
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:18:01.949Z]: your problem works the same way :) See if you can use what we did to try this on your own.
TUCKER @ [2018-05-08T20:18:14.858Z]: ok
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-08T20:18:23.762Z]: Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!
lesson_name: Distance on the Coordinate Plane II

Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-09T19:27:30.898Z]: You've got it.  Let's try a similar example.  Can you please shade half of this?
Rebecca @ [2018-05-09T19:28:09.982Z]: ok
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-09T19:28:28.722Z]: Perfect, here we have 1/2.  what fraction would be **equivalent** to 1 whole then?
Rebecca @ [2018-05-09T19:28:55.999Z]: 0k
Rebecca @ [2018-05-09T19:29:14.544Z]: what next
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-09T19:29:18.705Z]: Let's check to see if that makes sense.  is 1/2 equal (the same) as 1 ?
Rebecca @ [2018-05-09T19:29:29.855Z]: ya
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-09T19:30:03.356Z]: Is eating 1/2 of a cookie the same as eating 1 whole cookie?

Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-09T19:30:47.416Z]: You're right.  How many 1/2 cookies would we need to combine to make 1 whole cookie?
Rebecca @ [2018-05-09T19:30:57.538Z]: 2
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-09T19:31:07.525Z]: :) absolutely!
Rebecca @ [2018-05-09T19:31:23.682Z]: ok what next
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-09T19:31:52.342Z]: We see that 2/2 is equivalent to 1 whole... because if our whole is split into 2 equal parts, we need two of them :)  How many 1/2 cookies would we need to make 2 whole cookies?

Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-09T19:32:44.190Z]: How many 1/2 cookies would we need to make 2 whole cookies?
Rebecca @ [2018-05-09T19:32:52.594Z]: 4
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-09T19:33:08.513Z]: You've got it!  we know that 4/2 is equivalent to 2 wholes

transcript:
Server Notice @ [2018-05-10T20:05:22.649Z]: This conversation will be saved.

Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:05:22.650Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Would you like me to type or talk?
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:05:31.080Z]: Type please.
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:05:46.505Z]: What does it mean for something to be 'dependent' ?
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:06:19.083Z]: I do not know
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:06:41.355Z]: Okay, for example, my young children depend on me to make their food and clean their clothes... they cannot do it without me... what do you think 'dependent' means?
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:07:50.508Z]: Oh, sorry! I think dependent means to depend on somebody or something
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:08:04.662Z]: :) absolutely! it works the same in math... dependent qualities need something else to make sense and independent make sense on their own
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:08:45.741Z]: Oh ok, I thought there would be a math definition that was different.
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:09:36.129Z]: Luckily this time they work the same way :)  for example, apples are $2.25 per pound. Since I need to know the amount of pounds I have in order to find the price... is this dependent or independent ?
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:09:55.623Z]: Dependent?
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:10:54.826Z]: :) absolutely!
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:11:05.421Z]: Yay!!
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:12:06.706Z]: How do you know if a number is independent or dependent
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:12:29.025Z]: Let's use our example to see
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:12:52.165Z]: If I say I have 5 apples, does it depend on anything else to find it (like finding the price did) ?
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:13:05.880Z]: No.
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:13:35.473Z]: You're right, so just a single number, (the number of apples) is independent... it doesn't need anything else to find it
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:14:22.996Z]: ok
Mrs. Kathryn @ [2018-05-10T20:14:40.951Z]: I think you have it from here! Keep up the awesome work! See if you can use what we did to try this on your own.
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:14:53.640Z]: This equation above is dependent, right?
Sabella @ [2018-05-10T20:15:14.224Z]: Thank you for the encouragment

Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:36:46.497Z]: That's right
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:36:53.109Z]: What size container are we seeing if that fits into?
Sarai @ [2018-05-09T19:37:47.183Z]: 1 gallon container
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:38:10.701Z]: that's' right
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:38:16.729Z]: So what two equal parts can we split 1 gallon into?
Sarai @ [2018-05-09T19:38:40.192Z]: i dont know
Sarai @ [2018-05-09T19:39:39.624Z]: 4/8 and 4/8
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:39:43.229Z]: What is 1 whole divided by 2 ?
Sarai @ [2018-05-09T19:40:25.362Z]: 4/8 and 4/8

Sarai @ [2018-05-09T19:41:03.873Z]: yes :)

Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:41:25.546Z]: 3/8 is ☐ than 1/2 ? Greater or Less?

Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:42:15.795Z]: right
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:42:21.544Z]: 1/4 is ☐ than 1/2 ? Greater or Less?

Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:42:45.889Z]: Good
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:42:54.551Z]: if we mix two parts that are both less than 1/2, the total will be ☐ than 1 whole?
Sarai @ [2018-05-09T19:43:00.173Z]: thankyou
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:43:15.181Z]: Do you have any questions before you continue on your own?

Sarai @ [2018-05-09T19:45:28.961Z]: can you go over the steps one more time
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-09T19:46:12.624Z]: Well 3/8 and 1/4 are *both* less than 1/2 ... so that means the total will be less than 1 whole

Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:17:56.002Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Would you like me to type or talk?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:18:31.959Z]: hi,..... ,..type!
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:19:25.508Z]: What digit do we subtract first?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:20:07.537Z]: 3&2 ?
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:20:58.521Z]: that's right, and do you have to regroup to solve that?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:21:25.757Z]: yes! ?
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:21:32.501Z]: Well what does regrouping mean?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:23:17.560Z]: hum,to,....?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:23:49.312Z]: I don't know:(
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:23:58.855Z]: Regrouping is the same as 'borrowing'
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:24:05.710Z]: Do you have to borrow to do 3-2 ?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:24:24.925Z]: no...
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:24:46.466Z]: that's right, so we just have 3-2 = 1 in the first box
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:24:55.390Z]: Now look at the tens place: 2 - ☐ = 6 ?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:26:04.220Z]: nothing = to 2- enethang
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:26:35.668Z]: So since 2 is *less than 6* what do we have to do to solve that?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:26:55.075Z]: BARWO
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:27:22.610Z]: Yes, so after we borrow, what do we write above the 2 ?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:28:26.653Z]: a,hum,a 3
David @ [2018-05-10T14:28:32.222Z]: ?
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:28:36.918Z]: Well we regroup 1 hundred into 10 tens
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:28:40.778Z]: What is 10 tens + 2 tens?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:29:04.164Z]: 30?
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:29:18.825Z]: what is 10 + 2 ?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:29:26.267Z]: 12
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:29:59.708Z]: Right, so after we regroup we write 12 above the 2 .... Does that make sense?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:30:39.110Z]: yes, :(
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:31:40.565Z]: So 12 - ☐ = 6 ?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:32:25.185Z]: 12-5=6
David @ [2018-05-10T14:32:30.548Z]: 5
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:32:58.997Z]: Very close but not quite, please check your work
David @ [2018-05-10T14:33:32.477Z]: oh,6
David @ [2018-05-10T14:33:33.846Z]: 6
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:33:48.302Z]: that's right!
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:33:49.488Z]: Do you think you have it from here?
David @ [2018-05-10T14:34:51.213Z]: I think so
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-10T14:34:57.873Z]: Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!
David @ [2018-05-10T14:35:06.777Z]: by,you to

Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:18:35.265Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Would you like me to type or talk?
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:18:46.442Z]: Type
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:19:12.415Z]: I need help with questions like these.
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:19:33.034Z]: ok, Let's take a look at an example together.
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:19:50.103Z]: What does 5.127 round to the tenths place?
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:20:06.384Z]: uh, 5.1?
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:20:15.501Z]: that's right
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:20:33.739Z]: What about 5.927 ?
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:20:38.000Z]: can i write?
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:20:50.513Z]: can i write the answer?
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:21:06.581Z]: um, 5.9
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:21:42.512Z]: Ok try writing that one
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:22:11.107Z]: yes ma'am. did i get it right?
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:22:19.631Z]: Right very good!
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:22:41.904Z]: So now does the tenths place **change** when you round 5.■27 to the tenths?
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:23:10.142Z]: The tenths place is gone
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:23:50.414Z]: so, when it is rounded to the nearest 1 it is 5
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:24:08.168Z]: that's true, but no matter **what** is in the tenths place, it will stay the same, right?
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:24:37.759Z]: yes ma'am. we can round another way too
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:25:17.205Z]: So no matter what is in the space 5.■27 will round to 5.■ to the tenths place
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:25:22.827Z]: What about the **hundredths** place?
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:25:43.311Z]: it will be the same
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:26:08.125Z]: What is in the hundredths digit of 5.■27 ?
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:26:47.864Z]: i forgot. was it 4?
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:27:02.287Z]: look
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:27:03.885Z]: Look at the picture carefully
Stevie @ [2018-05-08T18:32:38.763Z]: 2
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:33:56.959Z]: that's' right
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:34:06.414Z]: What is to the right of the 2 in 5.■27 ?
Ms. Dominique @ [2018-05-08T18:37:49.724Z]: I haven't heard from you in a few minutes... Are you still there?

Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:29:49.063Z]: ![Image](https://content.thinkthroughmath.com/live_teaching_images%2F11ca3d38-0f37-4fb2-9d27-ed12f6ce81b9%2F94231H2.png)

transcript:
Server Notice @ [2018-05-09T17:19:47.514Z]: This conversation will be saved.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:19:47.515Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Your device does not support chat audio. We need to type. Ready?
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:20:06.058Z]: Yep
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:20:29.022Z]: Let's look at an example together.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:20:38.057Z]: What is 1/2 of 6?
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:21:11.351Z]: 3, ma'am
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:22:03.551Z]: yes, is that more or less than 6?
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:22:12.722Z]: Less.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:23:13.305Z]: Is 1/2 more or less than 1 whole?
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:23:32.973Z]: Less, ma'am.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:24:18.356Z]: So if you multiply by a fraction less than 1... you get just a part of that number
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:24:20.890Z]: 1/2 x 6 = 3
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:24:26.432Z]: 3 is just a part of 6
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:24:28.798Z]: Does that make sense?
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:24:43.538Z]: Yes ma'am.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:25:01.164Z]: Is 7/8 more or less than 1 whole?
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:25:17.737Z]: Less, ma'am
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:25:52.593Z]: yes, so if you multiply 7/8 by 1 3/4..
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:26:01.763Z]: should the answer be more or less than 1 3/4?
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:26:13.431Z]: More.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:26:39.894Z]: remember that 7/8 is less than 1 whole
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:26:48.703Z]: Oh, less.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:28:01.037Z]: exactly
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:28:08.599Z]: just a 'part' of 1 3/4
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:28:11.982Z]: But Miss, I still don't understand how to find the answer. How to prove if his answer is right or wrong.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:29:08.754Z]: You are trying to decide if 9/4 is correct
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:29:22.021Z]: What mixed number is 9/4 equal to?
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:29:53.667Z]: Please excuse me miss, I am working out the problem.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:30:17.525Z]: ok
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:30:33.029Z]: 2 1/4? Or is it 1 2/4?
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:30:41.250Z]: 2 1/4 is corrrect
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:30:48.763Z]: Is that smaller than 1 3/4?
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:31:00.452Z]: No
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:31:15.729Z]: correct
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:31:42.200Z]: and you know that is 7/8 is less than 1 whole.. the answer must be 'less than' 1 3/4
Mariyah @ [2018-05-09T17:31:58.846Z]: Yes
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T17:32:28.576Z]: I think you have it from here! Keep up the awesome work!

Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:31:38.754Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Would you like me to type or talk?
Pedro @ [2018-05-09T14:32:01.968Z]: type
Pedro @ [2018-05-09T14:32:15.374Z]: :)
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:32:29.999Z]: sure
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:32:33.349Z]: What does it mean to complete ONE trip to the beach?
Pedro @ [2018-05-09T14:32:53.134Z]: 219
Pedro @ [2018-05-09T14:33:39.263Z]: ;)
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:34:32.877Z]: That does not answer my question. Please read it carefully.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:35:30.481Z]: If you take a 'trip' to the beach, does that include going to and coming back?
Pedro @ [2018-05-09T14:36:05.565Z]: -yes
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:36:36.467Z]: exactly, what does the 219 mean?
Pedro @ [2018-05-09T14:37:20.814Z]: to the beach
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:37:47.916Z]: ok, miles 'to the beach'
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:37:59.897Z]: Would it also be 219 miles 'home from the beach'?
Pedro @ [2018-05-09T14:38:23.189Z]: yes
Pedro @ [2018-05-09T14:39:07.986Z]: but why
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:41:01.366Z]: To find the miles in a 'trip' you have to use the miles both ways.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:41:17.480Z]: 219 miles 'to the beach' AND 219 miles 'home from the beach'
Pedro @ [2018-05-09T14:41:34.110Z]: I don't get you
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:41:46.779Z]: How many miles is that?
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:41:54.982Z]: 219 there and 219 back home?
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:42:17.330Z]: How can you use the 'parts' of the trip to find the total?

transcript:
Server Notice @ [2018-05-09T14:53:26.788Z]: This conversation will be saved.
Server Notice @ [2018-05-09T14:53:26.790Z]: Your device supports Web RTC audio
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:53:26.797Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Would you like me to type or talk?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T14:53:33.469Z]: Hi
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T14:54:05.220Z]: Type
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:54:22.553Z]: sure
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:54:37.457Z]: What does the first help tell you might be helpful when subtracting fractions?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T14:55:15.416Z]: To use equivalent fractions
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:55:57.082Z]: ok great, will they have a common denominator?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T14:56:19.621Z]: Mabey
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:56:51.042Z]: Can you add/subtract fractions with a common denominator?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T14:57:29.558Z]: Add sometimes
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T14:57:54.760Z]: Both acully
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:58:06.228Z]: yes
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:58:39.488Z]: Do you see that 8 is the common denominator for 1/8 and 3/4?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T14:59:34.688Z]: Yes I do
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T14:59:52.839Z]: How did they make the equivalent fraction for 3/4?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:00:44.798Z]: Not sure
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:01:23.871Z]: What can you multiply any number by and not change the value?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:01:56.719Z]: The numerator
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:02:09.089Z]: by what number?
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:02:22.789Z]: Let's look at an example together.
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:02:25.877Z]: 5 x _ = 5
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:02:31.120Z]: 4
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:03:01.345Z]: not quite,
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:03:06.938Z]: 5 x 4 = 20
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:03:10.614Z]: 5 x ___ = 5
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:03:18.142Z]: 1
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:03:32.824Z]: yes, 1 whole
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:03:48.854Z]: Can you think of a fraction that is equal to 1 whole?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:04:23.723Z]: 4/4 and 8/8
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:04:58.710Z]: ok great :)
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:05:07.975Z]: What did they multiply 4 by to make 8?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:05:19.792Z]: 2
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:05:42.699Z]: exactly
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:05:52.072Z]: and what did they multiply 3 by to make 6?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:06:01.642Z]: 2
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:06:28.639Z]: exactly, and what you do you know about 2/2?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:06:43.889Z]: Equals 1 whole
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:07:01.327Z]: yes, so do you see they multiplied 3/4 x 2/2 to make 6/8?
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:07:06.144Z]: They used a form of 1 whole?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:07:25.183Z]: Ok
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:08:19.562Z]: in this problem....
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:08:34.261Z]: think about creating equivalent fractions with a common denominator
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:08:44.889Z]: Ok
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:09:26.853Z]: See if you can use what we did to try this on your own.
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:10:07.754Z]: Ok but what do I do
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:10:34.910Z]: 6/7 - 3/4
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:10:40.596Z]: What might you use for a common denominator?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:11:05.107Z]: Muptiplecaton
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:11:19.304Z]: Multiplication
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:11:48.645Z]: yes, you can multiply by a form of 1 whole.. what number will you try to get for the common denominator?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:12:12.610Z]: 32
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:12:33.723Z]: For 7 and 4?
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:12:55.496Z]: Oh my bad ok 28
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:13:23.638Z]: yes, 28 :)
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:13:31.375Z]: 6/7 = ?/28
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:14:10.426Z]: I’m not sure how to multiply this
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:14:39.814Z]: What do you multpiply 7 by to make 28?
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:14:51.133Z]: You can try it on the whiteboard.
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:15:34.894Z]: I can’t it won’t let me draw for some reason
Jaxon @ [2018-05-09T15:16:01.359Z]: 7 x 4 = 28
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:16:05.545Z]: yes
Mrs. Amy @ [2018-05-09T15:16:21.573Z]: so what will you multiply 6 by?

Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T14:53:18.233Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Would you like me to type or talk?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:53:27.521Z]: type
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:54:16.384Z]: i don't even know how to divide decimals
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T14:54:24.714Z]: Hello! What is one way we can divide a decimal?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:54:54.650Z]: do it like long division
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T14:55:21.495Z]: We could! Let's use an example on the board
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T14:55:35.707Z]: How can we show 2.25 ÷ 9?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:55:52.814Z]: what do you mean
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T14:56:18.071Z]: Let's think, how can you think of 2.25 as money?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:56:41.123Z]: 2 dollars and one quarter
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T14:57:11.034Z]: Awesome! Sometimes it helps to change a decimal to a whole number to help us divide, ok?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:57:29.185Z]: ok
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:58:01.396Z]: but having a quarter is not a whole
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T14:58:06.050Z]: So how many pennies would I need to show $2.25?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:58:15.126Z]: 225
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:58:45.278Z]: oh
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T14:58:53.978Z]: Exactly! So we can think of 2.25 as 225 pennies to help us divide. Does that make sense?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:58:55.193Z]: 225 is the whole
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:59:01.863Z]: yes
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T14:59:30.056Z]: so 225 divided by nine
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T14:59:32.148Z]: Awesome! Now how can I actually divide 225 and 9?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T15:00:02.294Z]: by long division
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T15:00:14.907Z]: Ok! can you show me on the board?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T15:00:41.223Z]: how
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T15:01:06.291Z]: You can draw on the board :)
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T15:02:35.556Z]: 25
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T15:02:45.745Z]: Awesome work! So we have 25 pennies. How can you write 25 pennies as a decimal?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T15:03:08.137Z]: 2.5
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T15:03:38.555Z]: That would be 2 dollars and 50 cents.
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T15:03:51.330Z]: opps 0.25
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T15:03:55.560Z]: right
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T15:04:04.961Z]: ??
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T15:04:19.460Z]: Awesome work! So 2.25 ÷ 9 = 0.25, do you see how we used whole numbers and money to help us find that?
Kunaal @ [2018-05-09T15:04:44.903Z]: yes and thank you!

JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:40:02.523Z]: ok
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:40:05.358Z]: Let's use an example with 35 + 17. How can you break **each number** apart into tens and ones first?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:40:46.638Z]: 30 5
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:40:50.048Z]: 10 7
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:41:15.244Z]: Perfect! How many tens are in 30?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:41:19.158Z]: 35 is 30 and 5
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:41:27.189Z]: 3
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:41:42.226Z]: Yes! So i can say 3 tens and 5 ones, do you see that?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:41:43.918Z]: 17 is 10
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:41:55.531Z]: So i can say 3 tens and 5 ones, do you see that?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:42:27.036Z]: yes
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:42:44.870Z]: Awesome! So we have 3 tens and 5 ones and 1 ten and 7 ones. How can we find the total **ones** first?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:43:09.888Z]: add them together
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:43:28.790Z]: right! So how many total ones do we have?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:43:34.054Z]: see i don't know how to do it im never going to get it right
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:43:45.467Z]: 4
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:44:02.164Z]: If we have 5 ones and 7 ones, what is our total if we're adding?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:44:41.682Z]: 52
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:45:02.175Z]: How can we add 5 + 7?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:45:41.649Z]: 7 + 5 = 12
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:46:18.090Z]: Awesome! so we have 12 ones. How can we find how many total **tens** we have?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:47:06.252Z]: 3 + 1 = 4 + 1 = 5
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:47:35.703Z]: because you bring the 1 from 12 on top of 3 and add
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:47:58.126Z]: Remember, we want to keep them separate :) So we have 12 total ones. How many total tens do we have?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:48:49.855Z]: 8 ones :)
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:49:05.451Z]: That does not answer my question. Please read it again carefully :)
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:49:07.370Z]: is it right :(
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:49:26.210Z]: @
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:49:35.445Z]: disney land
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:49:47.880Z]: If we have 3 tens and 1 ten, how can we find the total tens we have?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:49:51.060Z]: opps didnt mean to send
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:50:10.006Z]: 4
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:50:38.459Z]: Yes! So we can say 3 tens and 5 ones + 1 ten and 7 ones equals 4 tens and 12 ones. Do you see that?
JALISA @ [2018-05-09T17:50:50.696Z]: yes
Mrs. Lynae @ [2018-05-09T17:50:58.491Z]: Awesome work! See if you can use what we did to try this on your own. Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!

Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-09T15:40:37.848Z]: What strategy would you use to find the missing numbers?

Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-09T15:41:26.260Z]: why do you think that strategy would work?

Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-09T15:44:23.414Z]: it was!
Callie @ [2018-05-09T15:44:32.443Z]: oh ok!
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-09T15:44:49.086Z]: what could you divide to find n for **n x 3/4 = 5/2**?

Callie @ [2018-05-09T15:46:13.908Z]: oh sorry you divide 3/4 and 5/5 togethr

Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-09T15:47:10.100Z]: 5/2 ÷  3/4 or 3/4 ÷  5/2?

Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:51:44.874Z]: First, what do you think **volume** is?
Addison @ [2018-05-07T21:52:22.225Z]: The cubes in the block.
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:52:31.445Z]: excellent!
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:52:44.950Z]: What strategy would you use to make a total volume that is greater than 30?
Addison @ [2018-05-07T21:53:29.469Z]: Addition?
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:53:37.666Z]: wonderful!
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:53:41.649Z]: What would you do first?
Addison @ [2018-05-07T21:54:14.156Z]: Multiply the length and width.
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:54:30.759Z]: and after that?
Addison @ [2018-05-07T21:55:00.610Z]: I'm not sure about that.
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:55:31.275Z]: Let's look at the helps for this problem. Do you know where to find 1 help and 2 help?
Addison @ [2018-05-07T21:55:37.262Z]: Yes
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:55:44.333Z]: Please read 1 help and 2 help. Let me know when you finish reading, okay?
Addison @ [2018-05-07T21:55:50.213Z]: Okay.
Addison @ [2018-05-07T21:56:45.044Z]: I don't get it but I'm done.
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:57:10.146Z]: okay!
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:57:17.688Z]: We do length x width x height
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:57:26.944Z]: so you can think of a volume as layers of area
Addison @ [2018-05-07T21:57:38.767Z]: Ok
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:58:09.067Z]: To make a combined volume that is greater than 30 unit cubes, does it make more sense to...
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:58:20.878Z]: use the **largest** or the **smallest** blocks?
Addison @ [2018-05-07T21:58:35.295Z]: Smallest
Mrs. Audrey @ [2018-05-07T21:58:45.502Z]: How can you convince me that your reasoning makes sense?

THUY @ [2018-05-08T14:54:54.984Z]: 1
Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-08T14:55:32.778Z]: I am understanding you to say that 1 x 1 = 2. Is that true?

Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-08T14:56:17.951Z]: Did you know that 1 x 1 = 1?
THUY @ [2018-05-08T14:56:41.802Z]: no
Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-08T14:56:48.815Z]: See if you can use what we did to try this on your own.

Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-09T19:32:23.322Z]: 48 inches = 4 feet. Still with me?

Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-09T19:33:54.353Z]: Using the formula, we now have SA = 4π • 48(inches)²

Angie @ [2018-05-09T14:45:08.283Z]: type please
Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-09T14:45:23.314Z]: What do they mean by 'related fact'?
Angie @ [2018-05-09T14:47:11.036Z]: an equivalent fraction?
Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-09T14:48:04.572Z]: Do you remember that multiplication and division are **opposite** operations?
Angie @ [2018-05-09T14:48:45.135Z]: yes i remember
Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-09T14:49:04.512Z]: Example: 1/2 ÷ 4/5 = 5/8 means 5/8 x 4/5 = 1/2.
Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-09T14:49:10.626Z]: Are you with me so far?
Angie @ [2018-05-09T14:49:16.725Z]: yea
Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-09T14:49:31.734Z]: So it's no different when there is a variable:1/2 ÷ 4/5 = n is the same as n x 4/5 = 1/2.
Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-09T14:50:11.788Z]: See if you can use what we did to try this on your own.
Angie @ [2018-05-09T14:50:30.818Z]: okay i'll try
Mrs. Cheryl @ [2018-05-09T14:51:17.319Z]: Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!
lesson_name: Using the Relationship Between Multiplication and Division to Divide Fractions
